article.headline: New Orleans 70, New Mexico State 59
article.story: LAS CRUCES, N.M. (AP) -- Johnell Smith scored 18 points as New Orleans took advantage of an Aggie injury to beat New Mexico State 70-59 Thursday night. Smith ignited a 10-4 run early in the second half by scoring six points and giving New Orleans a 48-41 lead with 14:03 left. The team bolstered that lead to 56-45 after a couple of free throws from Smith with 11:50 left. New Mexico State made a slight comeback after Duane John connected on a three-point play, bringing the score to 58-54 with 9:07 left. But New Orleans (8-7, 2-0 Sun Belt) was too strong down the stretch, as it went on a 12-2 run to close out the game. Kelsey Crooks led the Aggies (7-6, 1-1 Sun Belt) with 14 points and eight rebounds. John chipped in with 10 points and eight boards as well. Victor Brown had 11 points and eight boards for New Orleans. The Aggies played the majority of the game without their leading rebounder and second leading scorer, James Moore. He left the game in the first half with just 4 points after spraining his right knee going up for a dunk. "They are a different team with Moore gone," said New Orleans coach Monte Towe. "We went inside and exposed their weakness and picked up a good win." Despite the injury to Moore, the Aggies out rebounded the Privateers 43-38. But New Orleans held the advantage of points in the paint, 28-18. The Aggies committed 17 turnovers, compared to only nine from New Orleans. "I thought we played a lot better in the second half," said Smith. "The injury to Moore really hurt them. I feel bad for him getting hurt, but I am happy we got the win." New Mexico State jumped out to an early 16-11 lead as the Aggies hit seven of their first nine shots. The Aggies managed to stretch their lead to 21-11 with 10:02 left, but then Moore left the game, and so did the Aggies' offense. "We definitely struggled after James (Moore) got hurt," said Aggie coach Lou Henson. "We don't have any other options in the post when he is out of the game, and they took advantage of that." With Moore gone, New Orleans wasted no time and went on a 23-11 run, with 10 of those points in the paint and took a 34-32 lead going into the second half. Moore is set to have an MRI Friday morning on his knee.
